msgstr ""

#. type: cindex
#: frames.texi.orig:1193
#, no-wrap
msgid "terminal emulators, mouse support"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: frames.texi.orig:1196
msgid "Some text terminals support mouse clicks in the terminal window."
msgstr ""

#. type: cindex
#: frames.texi.orig:1197
#, no-wrap
msgid "xterm"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: frames.texi.orig:1206
msgid ""
"In a terminal emulator which is compatible with @command{xterm}, you can use "
"@kbd{M-x xterm-mouse-mode} to give Emacs control over simple uses of the "
"mouse---basically, only non-modified single clicks are supported.  The "
"normal @command{xterm} mouse functionality for such clicks is still "
"available by holding down the @kbd{SHIFT} key when you press the mouse "
"button.  Xterm Mouse mode is a global minor mode (@pxref{Minor Modes}).  "
"Repeating the command turns the mode off again."
msgstr ""

#. type: findex
#: frames.texi.orig:1207
#, no-wrap
msgid "gpm-mouse-mode"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: frames.texi.orig:1211
msgid ""
"In the console on GNU/Linux, you can use @kbd{M-x gpm-mouse-mode} to enable "
"mouse support.  You must have the gpm server installed and running on your "
"system in order for this to work."
msgstr ""

